AGI - After the liberation of the French Olivier Grondeau>, arrested in October 2022 during a tourist trip and condemned for espionage, there are eight European citizens still held in Iran.
&nbsp;
They proclaim themselves innocent and NGOs consider them "obstages" used by Tehran to obtain the release of Iranians held abroad. Others may be detained without their case being made public, as sometimes authorities in individual countries recommend doing to negotiate with discretion their release.
&nbsp;
According to a French diplomatic source, Western prisoners in Iran are about 20, but here are the Europeans whose detention was made public. - Cecile Kohler>, teacher and his partner, Jacques Paris>, were arrested in May 2022 for "spionage" while visiting Iran. In September 2023, the Iranian judiciary announced that their investigations had been completed, opening the way to a possible process.
&nbsp;
They are "living slowly", said Noemie Kohler>, sister of Cecile, at the beginning of March, testifying the "inhuman conditions" of their detention. - Ahmadreza Djalali>, an Iranian-Swedish academic, was arrested during a visit to Iran in April 2016 and sentenced to death in 2017 for "spionage" for Israel. On 7 March Stockholm stated that it had "received very worrying information about the worsening" of its health conditions and asked for its "immediate release" to receive medical care "without delay".
&nbsp;
According to the Swedish Ministry of Foreign Affairs, from January 2024 a Swedish man of about twenty years has been detained in Iran, although the Swedish media claim that he is sought according to an international arrest warrant. - Mehran Raoof>, an Iranian-British human rights activist, was arrested in October 2020 and sentenced in August 2021 to 10 years and eight months in prison, according to Amnesty International, held for months in solitary confinement in the Evin prison in Tehran, from where last year he managed to send a letter describing the hard treatment reserved for people with dual citizenship. - Craig and Lindsay Foreman>, a British couple on the fifty that according to the BBC, was on the move around the world when she was arrested in Iran in January 2025.
&nbsp;
The following month they were formally charged with "spionage". - Nasrin Roshan>, an Iranian-British woman, was arrested in November 2023 at Tehran airport while preparing to leave the country and is currently serving a three-year imprisonment sentence in Evin, convicted of endangering national security. Human Rights Activists News Agency (HRANA) recently reported that the woman was hospitalized after losing knowledge.&nbsp;

